			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Most everyone keeps expounding the same fallicy.  You equate health insurance with health care.*  The government coerced system of employer supplied health insurance fosters this mentality.
<br />

<br />
That system is the root of the evil that is the health care system today.  The Doctor, hospital, clinic, whaterver, know that YOU aren't paying the bill, so YOU won't shop around, so they are all free to charge whatever they can fly past the insurance companies.  The evil HMO's were invented by the government (thank you again, Ted Kennedy) to try and curb some of that ever increasing spiral, and resulted in health care rationing instead.  (Unintended consequences strike again!)  In fact, you can't blame hospitals for the practice since they have to provide care for FREE to anyone who comes to their emergency rooms.  So, as the system breaks down farther, they close trauma centers and emergency rooms just so they can stay in business.  (Whoops!  There's those unintended consequences once more!  Just remember TANSTAAFL and maybe it won't happen to you.)
<br />

<br />
Simply having the government pick up the tab, which is what they are ALL moving towards, will just make it all worse.
<br />

<br />
We need to get back to everyone paying their own way, with their own money.  You will then shop around.  You will then not demand services that you don't need.  When people shop around, other people set up to get some of that business.  Prices come down, quality goes up.  It's called competition.  It's called a free market.  It's a good thing.
<br />

<br />
If the government really wanted to help, they could allow Medical Savings Accounts, where you put money tax deferred.  Spend it on medical bills only.  Anything not spent by the time you retire you can roll into retirement savings.  But NOOOOO, that would actually allow the individual to have some control, and people are too stupid to allow that.
<br />

<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/banghead.gif" alt="banghead" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
* I could care less how many po lille chillins gots no health insurance.  My children have been without health insurance more than once.  If they need health care, they get it.  I beg, borrow, or steal the money needed, and pay the doctor myself.  I also shop for a doctor who will give a break to a 'cash customer'.  More than one has gone out of their way to give discounts, or supply samples so we didn't need to pay for prescriptions.  And on that vein, more than one pharmacy will work with you with discounts, etc, if you are a 'cash customer'.
<br />

<br />

<br />
EDIT:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">People want nationalized healthcare because they believe healthcare is a "right." But no one has a right to healthcare. Rights do not give people the "right" to force others (such as doctors and taxpayers) to provide them with things they want or need. Such a "right" implies the absurd contradiction of having the "right" to violate the rights of others.
<br />

<br />
Rights only give people the freedom to obtain things from others through voluntary trade. Doctors have a moral right to try to make as much money as possible using their talents, just as plumbers, lawyers, and professional athletes have this right. The fact that obtaining healthcare might mean the difference between life and death does not give people the "right" to enslave doctors to their needs.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Doctors, and I add, <span style="font-weight: bold">and taxpayers</span>.
<br />

<br />
That's a GREAT article.<br />
