			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				At my current job I make $19,600 pre-tax.  It's not the best job, but it's putting me through college quite nicely, takes care of all my bills, and leaves me around  $600 a month play money after all expenses.  By my state's standards, I am only barely, if at all, above the poverty line.  Yet I still receive quality health care.
<br />

<br />
If your employer doesn't offer a health insurance package that's worth a crap, either switch jobs, start a movement within your own company towards better health insurance, or don't bitch if you're too complacent to do either.  I'm through Aetna, for God's sake.  One of those "big HMOs".  My plan is not an HMO plan.  For that matter, virtually every "big HMO" offers multiple plans with varying levels of coverage.  And by coverage I don't mean just monetary amount, I mean number of covered doctors and services, benefits, etc.  Half the people I work with were unaware that our medical options consisted of six different plans.  Most of them had the standard HMO plan, and it's, well, a standard HMO plan.  Choice of doctors is very limited, deductibles are quite high, seeing a doctor other than your PCP requires both a referral from your PCP and recurring authorizations from Aetna themselves.
<br />

<br />
Then there's my plan, which costs a whopping $10 a month more than the HMO plan.  It lets me choose what doctor I go to at will.  I have less of a deductible than on any of the other plans, and my copay is based on a 10% copay up to $100, if the percentage is more than $100, it's just a flat fee of $100 for me.  The rest of the benefits follow suit, they're far better.  This plan is also available to the public for like $30 a month more than it costs me through my employer.
<br />

<br />
Most people, frankly, don't know how to shop for health insurance.  They don't know what the various terms in the policy mean, they don't know how to find a good deal, etc.  If you take the time to learn, it's not difficult at all to find a solid healthcare provider that doesn't screw you over.
<br />

<br />
Flarestar Bladesinger<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
